         <handDesc>
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic" corresp="#p1 #p3">
                       <seg type="script"><date>14th-century, probably around the middle</date> script</seg> 
                       <date notBefore="1320" notAfter="1370"/>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red.</seg>
                       <seg type="rubrication"/>
                       <desc>Careful, regular; by a good scribe. መ has the loops tightly bound; ኖ of ancient shape,
                         without the overarching line above; ዲ of ancient shape, the vowel marker under the horizontal bottom line 
                         (verso side, line 5 from below); ሎ with the vowel marker set 
                         high above without linking line; ሣ of ancient shape (the right half-loop smaller, formed with a thin short line); 
                         ጥ has the legs drawn close to the bottom line. The word for God is written as one word. The psalm numbers are written in red, without dashes above and below, 
                        accompanied by a small rubricated crux ansata. Take-ups and take-downs at the end of many verses, marked by black lines.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
